    "narrative": "For our April 25th slate, the heart of our lineup is anchored by **Cal Raleigh** (71.30) and **Will Smith** (70.62). **Cal Raleigh** benefits significantly from a favorable matchup against Liberatore and a prime #2 spot in the order, while **Will Smith** draws a strong environment bolstered by favorable winds and an advantageous matchup against Colin Rea. **Geraldo Perdomo** also presents as a top-tier play today; despite the inherent volatility of the leadoff spot, his matchup against Germ\u00e1n M\u00e1rquez provides a massive 19% boost in SP skill, making him a high-floor selection for our scarcest category, stolen bases. \n\nThe optimizer\u2019s preference for **Bryson Stott** (66.12) and **Jonathan Aranda** (65.19) is driven by superior platoon splits against right-handed pitching, providing them higher efficiency scores than several bench alternatives. Notably, **Taylor Ward** represents a fascinating pivot; while his base projection is moderate, he carries a massive 16% park factor uplift, allowing him to maintain a 59.46 score even while facing the elite arm of Crochet. Conversely, **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (59.41) faces a grind against Gausman; while he remains a must-start due to talent, his score is slightly suppressed by a poor BvP history and a difficult pitching matchup.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today's card was bypassing **Gleyber Torres** (50.43). He was the final cut for our utility slot, ultimately edged out by **Matt Chapman** (55.93) due to **Matt Chapman**'s higher base projection and the additional utility provided by the \"Slow SP Delivery\" factor against Eury P\u00e9rez, which marginally improves his stolen base equity. We remain cautious regarding the risks inherent in our lineup: five of our starters, including **Will Smith**, **Bryson Stott**, **Geraldo Perdomo**, **Gavin Sheets**, and **Wenceel Perez**, are currently operating with \"Lineup Pending\" tags. If any of these names shift down in the order or are rested, we will need to re-evaluate our game cap management, particularly for **Wenceel Perez**, whose 44.34 efficiency score is already near our bench threshold.",
